'''Birutė Ciplijauskaitė''' (11 April 1929 in [[Kaunas]] – 19 June 2017) was a Lithuanian literary scholar and translator.<ref name="UW">{{Cite web |url=https://www.library.wisc.edu/news/2017/07/13/honoring-professor-birute-ciplijauskaite/ |title=Honoring Professor Biruté Ciplijauskaité |date=2017-07-13 |website=University of Wisconsin, Library News & Events |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref name="EP">{{Cite web |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2017/06/28/actualidad/1498647947_165646.html |title=Biruté Ciplijauskaité, el maduro conocimiento de la poesía española |last=Amusco |first=Alejandro Duque |date=2017-06-28 |website=El País |language=es |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref name="Mockūnas1991">{{cite book|last=Mockūnas|first=Liūtas|title=Pokalbių akiračiai: "Akiračių" interviu su išeivių kultūros veikėjais, 1969-1989|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8xkhAQAAMAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Vaga|isbn=978-5-415-00773-8|page=206|language=Lithuanian}}</ref> The daughter of physician and gynecologist, director of [[Klaipeda]] hospital, she attended Kaunas Conservatory and fled Lithuania during World War II. She graduated from the [[University of Tuebingen]] in 1956 and then the [[University of Montreal]].<ref name="UW" /> Ciplijauskaitė taught Spanish at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]] from 1960 until 2000, and was a professor from 1968.<ref name="UW" /> She received her PhD in Spanish and [[French language|French]] from [[List of Bryn Mawr College people|Bryn Mawr College]] in 1960.<ref name="UW" /><ref name="EP" /> Ciplijauskaitė has been an adviser for ''[[Lituanus]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lituanus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZF0MAQAAMAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Lituanus Foundation.|page=2}}</ref>
