The '''East Asian Library and the Gest Collection''' (pronounced "Guest") in the [[Princeton University Library]] is the university's principle collection of materials in Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, as well as works on Chinese, Japanese and Korean linguistics and literatures in Western languages.<ref>[https://library.princeton.edu/eastasian East Asian Library and Gest Collection].</ref> 

The '''Gest Oriental Library''' is named in honor of [[Guion Moore Gest]] (1864-1948), whose collection of Chinese books and manuscripts formed the Gest Chinese Research Library.{{sfnb|Tsien|1979| p = [https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/bitstream/handle/2142/39905/crl_40_05_405_opt.pdf?sequence=2 408-409]}} The Gest Research Library was officially opened  on February 13 (Chinese New Year's Day), 1926, at [[McGill University]] in Montreal. It was renamed the Gest Oriental Library when the collection was moved to Princeton in 1937.{{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 17] }} The library's holdings were expanded into Japanese and Korean after World War II to form one of the largest collections in North America. The Chinese collection is especially strong in [[Ming dynasty]] editions and works on [[traditional Chinese medicine]].<ref name="Wilkinson ">{{cite book |last = Wilkinson |first = Endymion |year = 2012 |title = Chinese History: A New Manual | |publisher = Harvard University Asia Center| location = Cambridge, MA |isbn = 9780674067158 |ref = harv}}, p. 974. </ref>

==History of the Gest Collection==
===The original collection===

Guion Moore Gest built one of the largest collections of Chinese language rare books in North America in spite of the fact that he was not especially wealthy and could not read Chinese. [[Hu Shi]], a prominent scholar who served as curator 1950-1952, noted that the collection, which "began as a hobby and developed into an investment, soon became a burden to a founder".{{sfnb|Hu|2013| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=sRVEAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=Hu+Gest+oriental+library+Princeton&source=bl&ots=ohWocJP_XG&sig=yjddXa-Bk_KBe7SDrH1SGdQjIqo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH-sjFx4fUAhUj0IMKHVEnABEQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Hu%20Gest%20oriental%20library%20Princeton&f=false 26]}}

Gest travelled often to Asia in the 1910s and 1920s on business for the Gest Engineering Company, which he founded and headed. As early as the 1890s he develolped an interest in Buddhism and bought a Japanese manuscript scroll. He retained [[Chen Baozhen]], a Chinese scholar who had been an imperial tutor, to locate and purchase books for his collection. Chen assembled more than 8,000 volumes, (''juan''?) mostly standard works. <ref>There is often confusion in English because a Chinese traditional string-sewn "book" can be made up of a number of ''juan'', that is, "volumes" or "fascicles." Often it is not clear whether "volume" means "book" in the Western sense or "fascicle." </ref> 

After Chen's death in 1900, Gest retained an agent in Beijing, Commander I.V. Gillis (1875-1948), a retired United States Naval Attaché. He spoke Mandarin Chinese fluently, but could not read classical Chinese texts that had not been punctuated. He developed intimate knowledge through many years of handling books, however, and a leading Chinese bibliographer who examined his collection and his catalogues wrote that "his knowledge of Chinese bibliography is exceptionally good". {{sfnb|Hu|2013| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=sRVEAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=Hu+Gest+oriental+library+Princeton&source=bl&ots=ohWocJP_XG&sig=yjddXa-Bk_KBe7SDrH1SGdQjIqo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH-sjFx4fUAhUj0IMKHVEnABEQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Hu%20Gest%20oriental%20library%20Princeton&f=false 179]}} Gillis' wife was a Manchu princess, and his web of personal relations led him to the [[Guangxu emperor]]'s tutor and other high officials with collections of useful volumes. <ref name="Wilkinson " />  Gest suffered from [[glaucoma]], and Gillis suggested that he try an eye medicine which was a specialty the Ma family of [[Dingxian]], [[Hebei]] province, who kept a shop in the capital. This medicine sparked Gest's interest in [[traditional Chinese medicine]] and in collecting books on the subject. {{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 17-19]}} 

Because Gest's funds were limited, Gillis bought selectively, concentrating on works printed in the Ming and Qing dynasties, which were of less interest to wealthy Chinese and Japanese collectors than works printed in the Song dynasty. He acquired "Palace editions," treatises printed by government agencies, commercial publishers, and manuscripts from all parts of the country. He did not always insist on rare editions, though he bought a great many. Gest and Gillis acquired some 500 works in 2,000 ''juan'' on Chinese medicine, the largest such collection in the West at the time.{{sfnb|Hu|1954| p = [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-31184-0_26#page-1  177-178]}} Probably the most important single work in the history of Chinese medicine, [[Li Shizhen]]'s ''[[Bencao gangmu]]'' (''The Compendium of Materia Medica''), for instance, was published in the 16th century, but the collection's edition is a 19th century reprint. Together with later additions, the collection offers material all aspects of medical thought and practice, as well as the history of Chinese science.{{sfnb|Cheng|1984| pp = 12, 15}}

Gillis' staff of three searched bookstores and examined private collections. Gillis had worked in American naval intelligence, and enjoyed using his training to demonstrate to his friends how to determine that the same person had used different typewriters by the similar weight of their strokes. {{sfnb|Hu|2013| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=sRVEAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=Hu+Gest+oriental+library+Princeton&source=bl&ots=ohWocJP_XG&sig=yjddXa-Bk_KBe7SDrH1SGdQjIqo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH-sjFx4fUAhUj0IMKHVEnABEQ6AEIUDAG#v=onepage&q=Hu%20Gest%20oriental%20library%20Princeton&f=false 179]}} He once verified the date of a purported Sung dynasty book by examining the paper fiber under a microscope. He and his staff marked missing or damaged pages with signed slips and had damaged books interleaved, rebound, and boxed. {{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 19]}} Gillis catalogued the books, which meant that they were ready to shelve upon arrival in North America, and he even crated and shipped the furniture and wall decorations that were used first at McGill and then at Princeton.<ref> {{cite|editor1-first = Dan |editor1-last = Hazen| editor2-first = James| editor2-last = Spohrer|first= Diane|last = Perushek|title = Building Area Studies Collections| chapter = Building Library Collections in East Asian Studies| location = Wiesbaden|publisher = Harrassowitz|p =[https://books.google.com/books?id=Jc6JBXvzJUMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Princeton%20Gest&f=false 138]}}</ref>

In 1928 Gest hired the third person responsible for the early buildup of the collection, [[Nancy Lee Swann]], a returned missionary who was then finishing her doctoral degree in Chinese studies at [[Columbia University]]. She moved to Toronto and supplied a professional competence needed to turn a collection of rarities into a working collection. The catalogue of the collection had been prepared by the first curator, whose Chinese was not adequate. Gillis called it "truly pathetic." Swann revised the catalogue and became curator in 1933.{{sfnb|Brooks|2008}} She remained curator until her retirement in 1946. Gest, Gillis, and Dr. Swann built the collection from some 232 titles in  8,000 fascicles in 1928 to close to 130,000 by the time the collection was moved to Princeton.{{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 17-18]}}

By 1932, Gest's Chinese collection at McGill was second in size only to that of the Library of Congress. Gest explained his motivations in building his collection and establishing the library at McGill:
:There has been no attempt at any time to buy in volume for quantity's sake alone, but the one object has been to obtain the best of the old works that could be secured and perpetuate them in a home where a full realization could be made by the Western World of the culture of China. ("A Statement from the Founder") <ref>quoted in Perushek (1985) p. 18
</ref>

Gest and Swann energetically promoted use of the collection. In 1933, Gest promoted a project for doctors at the [[Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research]] to research the use of [[acupuncture]] to stimulate the sympathetic nervous sysyem. Swann welcomed prominent sinologists and authors such as [[Berthold Laufer]] and [[L. Carrington Goodrich]], and [[Pearl S. Buck]], as well as applying for research funds with the [[American Council of Learned Societies]]. The Gest collection fell behind in its rivalry with the Library of Congress because McGill could not offer support.{{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 18, 20]}}

The economic crisis of the 1930s put the collection and the library at risk. After 1934, McGill could no longer pay Swann's salary or provide quarters for the collection and closed the Chinese studies program that had been started only a few years earlier.<ref>{{cite | title = McGill University: For the Advancement of Learning, Volume II, 1895-1971 |
first = Stanley Brice |last = Frost|publisher = McGill-Queens Press| year = 1984| place = Kingston and Montreal| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=_QzvEBNIxC8C&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=gest+memorial+collection+china&source=bl&ots=Ig1GeParxS&sig=fCtLrGCDu2uggKjAVgNJqsJgqEk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7woPIg7_UAhUIdT4KHXsLDlUQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=gest%20memorial%20collection%20china&f=false 143-144]| url = |  ref = none}}</ref>}Gest at first paid Swann's salary of $2,000 when he could, but his eyesight and business were both failing. For several years Swann worked without pay and Gillis used $10,000 of his own savings to purchase and ship acquisitions.{{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 17-18] }}

===The move to Princeton===
Gest explored selling the collection to Harvard or Yale universities, but finally turned to the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research for help in purchasing the collection back from McGill, and then donating it to the Princeton [[Institute for Advanced Studies]]{{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 21-22]}} The Institute, however, had no expertise in the area and the university had no program in Chinese studies.{{sfnb|Brooks|2008}} {{sfnb|Tsien|1979| p = [https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/bitstream/handle/2142/39905/crl_40_05_405_opt.pdf?sequence=2 408-409]}} In contrast to the spacious and comfortable rooms in Toronto, the collection was now housed in what Swann called "makeshift quarters" in the basement of 20 Nassau Street, a storefront building owned by the university. Dr. Swann, the only full-time staff member, had responsibility for all aspects of the library, from cataloging to checking out books to guiding visiting scholars through the collection. During a heavy storm, she had to rouse the janitorial staff to place barriers on the floor above to keep water from coming through.{{sfnb|Perushek|1985| p =[http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1388&context=jeal 21-22]}} 

Guion Moore Gest died in 1948, as did his longtime agent Gillis. Swann received a paycheck marked "FINAL". She protested that she was entitled to three months' notice, but the trustees of the Institute for Advanced Study extended her retirement by only two months.{{sfnb|Brooks|2008| }}
When Princeton's Firestone Library was completed in 1948, the Institute transferred the Gest Collection transferred there.{{sfnb|Axtell|2006| p = [https://books.google.com/books?id=ewuriq-17s4C&pg=PA461&lpg=PA461&dq=The+Gest+Oriental+Library+at+Princeton+University&source=bl&ots=VqMH7HYP7b&sig=Gryl_z2whAkos1nBzSOyJCUajIY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik3KaUjO3OAhWCMyYKHdLkAN44ChDoAQggMAE#v=onepage&q=The%20Gest%20Oriental%20Library%20at%20Princeton%20University&f=false 461]}}

===Postwar growth===
During World War II and the early post-war years, the university established programs in Chinese and Japanese studies, which required increased library holdings. From 1950 to 1952, the curator was [[Hu Shi]], distinguished Chinese scholar and former ambassador from China to the United States. {{sfnb|Hu|1954| p = [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-31184-0_26#page-1 177-178]}} Hu engaged James Tung (Dong Shigang) as his assistant, who became Curator and served from 1952 to 1977. {{sfnb|Brooks|2008| }} 

The collection expanded substantially under Tung's curatorship. <ref name="Gest " /> Princeton faculty member [[Frederick W. Mote]] guided further development on the Chinese side, and [[Marius Jansen ]] led a major expansion of Japanese holdings. The collection of Japanese historical documents and publications became particularly rich.{{sfnb|Yates|1987 | p = [http://library.princeton.edu/eastasian/EALJ/ejPDF.php?aKey=yates_charles_l.EALJ.v02.n01.p008.pdf 8-9]}}The collection was re-named the Princeton East Asian Library, though often called the Gest Library. In 1972 the collection was transferred to Palmer and Jones Halls.{{sfnb|Brooks|2008| }}

The collection at the time of the move to Princeton in 1937 held some 100,000 volumes (''juan''), 40% of which were manuscripts, early printings, and rare editions. The 24,000 volumes of works printed in the Ming dynasty made it one of the largest in the West.{{sfnb|Tsien|1979| p = [https://www.ideals.illinois.edu/bitstream/handle/2142/39905/crl_40_05_405_opt.pdf?sequence=2 408-409]}} After World War II, the collection became the third largest in the US, after the Harvard-Yenching collection (which it had once outranked), and the Library of Congress holdings, which are almost twice as large.{{sfnb|Brooks|2008| }} In 2016, the library held roughly 425,000 volumes of Chinese books, with a special strength in pre-modern literature and history; some 163,000 volumes of Japanese language book; a smaller collection of Korean language books; and  more than 20,000 western language volumes. Acquisition librarians specialize in each of the major areas.<ref name="Gest ">{{cite| url = http://eastasianlib.princeton.edu/history.htm |title = History of the East Asian Library and the Gest Collection, Princeton University| publisher = East Asian Library and Gest Collection | ref = none}} </ref> 

Professor Ch'u Wan-li (Qu Wanli; 1907-1979), Curator of the National Central Library and the Institute of History and Philology, Academic Sinica, in Taiwan compiled a 671-page ''Catalogue of the Chinese Rare Books in the Gest Collection of the Princeton University'', published in Taiwan in 1974. {{sfnb|Cheng|1984| p = 15}}

==Publications==
The library publishes ''The Gest Library Journal'' (ISSN: 0891-0553), which started in 1986 and was renamed ''The East Asian Library Journal'' (ISSN: 1079-8021) in 1994. The contents are available free online. <ref>[http://library.princeton.edu/eastasian/EALJ/ East Asian Library Journal]</ref>

