'''Lawrence Foanaota''' [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], born on [[Malaita]],<ref>[http://penn.museum/documents/publications/expedition/PDFs/23-2/Ross.pdf "Shell Ornaments of Malaita"], Kay Ross, Penn Museum</ref> is a [[Solomon Islands|Solomon Islander]] [[archaeologist]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080516134913/http://www.worldarchaeologicalcongress.org/site/enews/enews_14.pdf World Archaeology Congress], February 2007</ref> He has been director & curator of the [[National Museum of the Solomon Islands]] since 1972.<ref>[http://www.pacificwrecks.com/people/museum/foanaota.html "Lawrence Foanaota"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705044459/http://www.pacificwrecks.com/people/museum/foanaota.html |date=5 July 2008 }}, Pacific Wrecks</ref><ref>[http://solomonstarnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3085&change=71&changeown=78&Itemid=26 "Museum gets new field kit"], ''Solomon Star'', 26 August 2008</ref> He has also been President of the Pacific Island Museums Association.<ref>[http://rspas.anu.edu.au/asiapacificweek/2006/heritage.php "Pacific Museums in Sustainable Heritage Development"], Australian National University, 2006</ref>

In 2009, the [[Queen of the Solomon Islands]], [[Elizabeth II]], appointed him Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]], for "services to the National Museum and to the community".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/jun/13/queens-birthday-honours-list-commonwealth "Queen's birthday honours list: Commonwealth"], ''The Guardian'', 13 June 2009</ref>

